## A Fictional Example: Demand Estimation for a New-to-World Device Feature

Consider a consumer electronics company -- call it Meridian Devices -- that is evaluating
investment in a new display technology for their tablet product line. The technology has no
market precedent; no competitor currently offers it, and it has never appeared in Meridian's
core tablet conjoint.

The core conjoint covers the standard attribute set: screen size, processor speed, storage,
battery life, connectivity, and price. It is calibrated against two years of historical sales
data and is used to produce all official demand estimates for the tablet portfolio.

The product team has already run a self-service conjoint focused specifically on display
features: resolution, refresh rate, color accuracy, and the new display technology. The
self-service conjoint was fielded with 800 respondents matched to the core tablet buyer
profile and designed by an economist with conjoint expertise.

**The question:** How does adding the new display technology to the next-generation tablet
affect expected first-year demand?

**The approach:**

1. Extract the part-worth utility for the new display technology from the self-service
   conjoint
2. Convert it to a willingness-to-pay estimate using price as the common attribute
   (both studies included price)
3. Apply that willingness-to-pay as an effective price adjustment in the core model's
   demand simulation for the next-generation tablet
4. Run the demand simulation with and without the adjustment to isolate the impact of
   the new feature
5. Report the output with explicit confidence intervals, flagging that the new feature
   estimate derives from a self-service conjoint rather than the core calibrated model

**What this produces:** A demand estimate that the product team can use in their investment
document, with transparent documentation of the methodology and its limitations. Not
a perfect estimate -- but a principled one that is better than either ignoring the feature
or proceeding without any quantitative basis.

