## Summary

Conjoint models are powerful tools for demand estimation, but they have a scope boundary
defined by the attributes included at design time. When product teams invest in
new-to-world innovation, they often find that the core conjoint cannot support their
investment decision.

Self-service conjoints offer a path to filling that gap -- but only when they are designed
rigorously, calibrated appropriately, and combined with core model estimates using a
principled methodology.

The key principles for product managers working in this space are:

- Treat self-service conjoint estimates as directional until calibrated against behavioral
  data
- Be explicit with stakeholders about which parts of a demand estimate come from which
  model
- Always report uncertainty intervals alongside point estimates
- Establish a quality review process for self-service conjoints that is independent of the
  product team running them
- Use Bayesian methods where possible to propagate uncertainty through combined models

The payoff for getting this right is significant: faster, more rigorous support for
high-stakes investment decisions in innovation, without waiting months for a full conjoint
refielding cycle.

